porate University -- tSection 4: Reflecting on the Tenure Journey: The Personal and Individual -- tIntroduction -- t13 Finding Energy From “Productive Anguish”: Avoiding Descents into Tenure-Track Darkness -- t14 Relationships, Associations, and Authority -- t15 It’s Not Me, It’s the Process -- t16 Jill Revisited—Still Struggling With Mental Illness Within Academia Post-Tenure -- t17 In the Trenches -- t18 Who Am I? Professional Identity on the Path to Tenure -- tConclusion -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTenure is a pivotal decision for the academy. If it is earned, it provides security and permanence, creating further academic freedom to pursue research and interests important to the institution and to society. If it is not earned, then the peer review process provides clarification for why it has not been earned. This book brings together lived experiences of academics around the time of the tenure decision. While the book is stand-alone, it has the same collection of authors who wrote about their tenure-track experiences in The Academic Gateway, making the pair of books a remarkable longitudinal collection.  The authors explore the complex relationship between academics, the academy as an ideal, and universities as an enactment of that ideal. Personal growth is evident and shows diversity of experience, as the maturing relationships with the role and workplace unfurl. Where tenure track is a very personal journey, the period around tenure is necessarily a form of engagement with peers. Yet it has challenges, particularly in a milieu where academic freedom is being nurtured. Individual authors negotiate their choices between their personal objectives and institutional mandates and policies. Simultaneously, after years in the tenure-track, they continue to be evolving as academics, whether through personal growth or by seeking changes in the academy itself.  Published in English.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCollege teachersxTenurezCanadavCase studies. 7aEDUCATION / Professional Development.2bisacsh  aAcademic freedom.  aFaculty.  aHigher education.  aTenure-track.  aTenure.1 aBadenhorst, C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBadenhorst, Cecile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlock, Lee Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Joan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChambers, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCobb, Cam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeer, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamm, Lyle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandford, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandford, Victoria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKornelsen, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcIvor, Onowa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLeod, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilley, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoore, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgilvie, Greg, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenney, S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPenney, Sharon, eco